Integration test case: Block cross-member access using encounterId in extraData (IDOR)
Description: Things that need to be checked: 

- The page does not render any prefilled answers, appointment details, or identifying information tied to Member A.

- Any API request that includes that encounterId returns:

HTTP 403/404 (not 200), and a response body that does not contain Member A data.

- If the app creates a new encounter for Member B instead, ensure the new encounterId differs from A’s and is owned by B.

Test Case ID: IT_001
Title: Member cannot open another member’s medical questionnaire by swapping encounterId in extraData
Type: Integration test (browser UI + backend authorization)
Priority: P1

Preconditions

Two member accounts exist: Member A and Member B.

Member A has (or can create) a valid encounter that produces a real encounterId.

Staging environment is used.

Test data: 

encounterId belonging to Member A:
097661a4-bf5f-47dd-86a2-ef7f1d1908b0

URL pattern:
/medical-questionnaire?flow=medical-questionnaire&direct=true&clearData=true&extraData=<urlencoded-json>

Where extraData JSON includes:
{"encounterId":"<uuid>"}

Steps

Log in as Member A on https://myezra-staging.ezra.com.

Start “Begin Medical Questionnaire” from A’s normal flow (so the encounter is legitimately created).

Capture Member A’s encounterId from the system (Network tab request payload or the extraData URL).

Log out.

Log in as Member B.

In the same browser session as Member B (authenticated as B), open the medical questionnaire URL that includes Member A’s encounterId, for example:
https://myezra-staging.ezra.com/medical-questionnaire?flow=medical-questionnaire&direct=true&clearData=true&extraData={...A encounterId...}
(Use the exact captured URL; no need to manually retype.)

Observe the UI behavior and capture the backend API calls made after page load (Network tab).

(Negative variation) Modify the encounterId slightly (e.g., change 1 character) and reload to test enumeration/guessing.

Expected results:

1. Member B must not be able to access Member A’s questionnaire or any medical data.

2. The system should respond with one of these safe outcomes:

3. Redirect to a safe starting point (e.g., dashboard or “start questionnaire” for B), without loading A’s data, or

4. Show an authorization error page/state.

5. Backend calls that fetch questionnaire/encounter data must return 403 or 404 for Member B.

6. No PHI appears in:

the UI,

API responses,

error messages,

console logs.





